Mean & Variance¶

In [349]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))

for target in np.unique(target_class):
    class_of_example=target
    example_instances = np.where(target_class==class_of_example)[0]
    example_df = pd.concat([long_x_train[example_instances].mean(axis=1),long_y_train[example_instances].mean(axis=1),long_z_train[example_instances].mean(axis=1)],1)
    example_df.columns = ["acc_x","acc_y","acc_z"]
    
    example_df["vec_x"] = example_df["acc_x"].cumsum()
    example_df["vec_y"] = example_df["acc_y"].cumsum()
    example_df["vec_z"] = example_df["acc_z"].cumsum()
    example_df["loc_x"] = example_df["vec_x"].cumsum()
    example_df["loc_y"] = example_df["vec_y"].cumsum()
    example_df["loc_z"] = example_df["vec_z"].cumsum()
    example_df = example_df[["loc_x","loc_y","loc_z"]]
    ax = fig.add_subplot(4, 2,target)
    
    x_mean,y_mean,z_mean = example_df.mean().values
    example_df["x_mean"] = x_mean
    example_df["y_mean"] = y_mean
    example_df["z_mean"] = z_mean
    example_df.plot(ax=ax)
    
    plt.title(f"Class {int(class_of_example)}")

plt.show()
In [357]:
first_rep_list = []
for example_instance in  range(long_x_train.shape[1]):
    example_df = pd.concat([long_x_train[example_instance],long_y_train[example_instance],long_z_train[example_instance]],1)
    example_df.columns = ["acc_x","acc_y","acc_z"]
    #example_df = example_df.shift()
    example_df["vec_x"] = example_df["acc_x"].cumsum()
    example_df["vec_y"] = example_df["acc_y"].cumsum()
    example_df["vec_z"] = example_df["acc_z"].cumsum()
    example_df["loc_x"] = example_df["vec_x"].cumsum()
    example_df["loc_y"] = example_df["vec_y"].cumsum()
    example_df["loc_z"] = example_df["vec_z"].cumsum()
    example_df = example_df[["loc_x","loc_y","loc_z"]]
    mean_value = example_df.mean(axis=0).sum()
    std_value = example_df.std(axis=0).sum()
    first_rep_list.append([mean_value,std_value])

Results¶

Mean and Std are able to differentiate classes 1,3,4,5,6. However, class 2,7 and 8 overlap since they are all actually closed loops. We could use a more advanced option than simply looking at mean & std by using PAA

Piecewise Aggregate App¶

In [425]:
from tslearn.piecewise import PiecewiseAggregateApproximation
In [426]:
paa = PiecewiseAggregateApproximation(n_segments=2)
In [428]:
example_dfs = []
for example_instance in  range(long_x_train.shape[1]):
    example_df = pd.concat([long_x_train[example_instance],long_y_train[example_instance],long_z_train[example_instance]],1)
    example_df.columns = ["acc_x","acc_y","acc_z"]
    #example_df = example_df.shift()
    example_df["vec_x"] = example_df["acc_x"].cumsum()
    example_df["vec_y"] = example_df["acc_y"].cumsum()
    example_df["vec_z"] = example_df["acc_z"].cumsum()
    example_df["loc_x"] = example_df["vec_x"].cumsum()
    example_df["loc_y"] = example_df["vec_y"].cumsum()
    example_df["loc_z"] = example_df["vec_z"].cumsum()
    example_df = example_df[["loc_x","loc_y","loc_z"]]
    example_dfs.append(example_df.values)

Results¶

We achieve 2 interval values for each time series and plot them to see the distribution of each class.In additon to representation 1 (mean - std), this method is able to differentiate class 7 and 8.However, since the direction of class 2 and 7 are the same, it could not be possible to differentiate them with this method as well.

As a result, we can use PAA compared to mean&std representation since it is more effective to separete classes visually. However, one can use also another method like SAX to differentiate class 2 and 7 as well
